{
  "title": "Extreme Weather Around the World",
  "transcript": "Do you know where the warmest spot on the planet is?[cite: 2] You can find one in a place called Death Valley.[cite: 2] Death Valley is one of the hottest places known to men, but it doesn't beat the world record for the highest temperature ever recorded.[cite: 2] That actually goes to a place called El Azizia in Libya, where the temperature soared to almost 60 degrees C in the early 1920s.[cite: 2] As far as extreme weather goes, you need not look further than Antarctica.[cite: 2] It's the coldest place on the earth, as well as the wettest, and at the same time the driest.[cite: 2] While this may seem odd, it actually makes sense when you delve deeper.[cite: 2] Antarctica is not inhabitable for large parts of the year due to the extreme cold.[cite: 2] The lowest temperature ever recorded there was around minus 90 degrees C.[cite: 2] At the same time, Antarctica happens to be the wettest place on the earth, but not because it has the most rain or snow.[cite: 2] The reason why Antarctica is the wettest place on the earth is that 98% of its surface is ice.[cite: 2] However, Antarctica never experiences rainfall, which makes it the driest place as well.[cite: 2] The ice there is so deep that nowhere else can an ice surface so thick at a depth of over 4,000 meters be seen.[cite: 2] That begs the question, where are the best and worst places in the world for weather?[cite: 2] The answer depends on the person asking the question.[cite: 2] We all have our own most hated types of weather.[cite: 2] If we can choose, according to a survey conducted by International Living, the top country for the weather was Italy, followed by France and Mexico.[cite: 2] What do you think?[cite: 2] Do you know anywhere better?[cite: 2]",
